// GC Stress Pattern 1: Allocation Storm
//
// Purpose: Exercises the GC's ability to handle rapid creation and immediate
// abandonment of mixed object types. Every iteration allocates a string
// (via concatenation), an array, and a dictionary — then discards all of them.
//
// What this catches:
// - GC failing to sweep short-lived objects (memory leak)
// - Incorrect root scanning when many temporaries exist on the stack
// - Intern table issues when many unique strings are created and abandoned
// - Crashes during collection when allocation triggers GC mid-expression
//
// The periodic collectGarbage() every 20 iterations forces collection while
// the loop variables and temporaries are still on the stack, ensuring the
// GC correctly identifies live vs dead objects during iteration.

record Node(value, next);

for (var i = 0; i < 200; i = i + 1) {
  // Each concat creates a unique interned string; the array and dict are
  // fresh heap objects. All three become garbage at end of iteration since
  // nothing outside this scope references them.
  var tmp = "storm" + str(i) + "x";
  var arr = newArray();
  arrayPush(arr, tmp);
  arrayPush(arr, newArray());  // nested array — tests multi-level unreachable graphs
  var d = dictNew();
  dictSet(d, "k", tmp);       // dict references the string — both die together
  if (i % 20 == 0) collectGarbage();
}
collectGarbage();  // final sweep of remaining iteration garbage
print "pattern 1 (allocation storm): passed";
